Cooking Patterns
Pattern 1: Weeknight Express (Under 30 Minutes)
Quick, satisfying meals for busy schedules:
- One-pan/one-pot meals
- Sheet pan dinners
- Stir-fry with pre-prepped aromatics
- Pasta with pantry sauce
- Grain bowls with mix-and-match toppings

Pattern 2: Weekend Project Cook
Ambitious dishes for skill building:
- Homemade pasta or bread
- Slow-braised meats (4-6 hours)
- Multi-component curries with fresh spice blends
- Pastry and dessert fundamentals
- Fermentation projects (kimchi, pickles, sourdough starter)

Pattern 3: Ingredient Rescue
Making great food from what you have:
- Fridge audit and ingredient prioritization
- Flexible template recipes (fried rice, frittata, soup, stir-fry)
- Leftover transformation techniques
- Pantry staple magic (canned beans, pasta, eggs, rice)
- Zero-waste cooking principles

Best Practices
Cooking
- Taste as you go — seasoning in layers beats seasoning at the end
- Mise en place is not optional — read the entire recipe before starting
- High heat + dry surface = Maillard reaction = flavor
- Salt is a flavor amplifier, not just a seasoning — use it boldly
- Acid (lemon, vinegar) is the most underused tool — it brightens everything

Learning
- Master 5 weeknight recipes before expanding your repertoire
- Understand WHY a technique works, not just HOW
- Failures are data — burned garlic teaches you about heat control
- Copy before you create — learn classic recipes before improvising
- Cook for others — feedback accelerates growth

Kitchen Management
- Sharp knife = safe knife — hone before every session
- Clean as you go — a cluttered station is a slow station
- Invest in a few quality tools over many cheap ones (chef's knife, cast iron, Dutch oven)
- Label and date everything in the fridge and freezer
- Food safety is non-negotiable (temperature danger zone: 4°C - 60°C)

